occurrenceRemarks: With Don Fraser; a visit to see what was around. There was a lot of water around! The weather at the start was sunny and 88 degrees, with a light breeze (I had no cell phone reception, so I got the temperature from Don's SUV; the "feels like" temperature was probably 88-90 degrees), We drove North Grade Road, spent some time at the (graffiti-laden!) wooden bridge over the Little Withlacoochee River, then turned "left" onto River Road. We took River Road to County Road 471, then drove south back to North Grade Road, which we drove again to the bridge over the Little Withlacoochee River. We left around 1400, when the weather was sunny and hot (probably with a "feels like" temperature >100 degrees), with a light breeze. On the way back, we stopped at the Richloam General Store for refreshments. These are my cell-phone images, uploaded before my camera images because my phone is GPS-enabled, thus automatically geo-locating them. I will upload "snips" of my (non-GPS-enabled) camera photographs at a later date. In some cases, I will replace the inferior cell-phone images of some species with superior camera images.
verbatimLocality: Florida, Sumter, Withlacoochee State Forest, Richloam Tract, North Grade Road and River Road

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. An investigation of the evolution and taxonomy of the true blueberries (Vaccinium section Cyanococcus).]; Clonal shrub 0.7 m tall; older stems green, becoming brown and fissured at base of plant; new stems green flushed red; leaves shiny deep green above, pale green beneath; pedicels, hypanthium, and limb red; corolla creamy white flushed pink at apex, style slightly exserted; fruit lustrous green flushed red, limb red . Common.
habitat: Longleaf pine forest with Drosera sp., Ilex coriacea, Lyonia ferruginea, Morella cerifera, Pinus palustris, Quercus geminata, Q. myrtifolia, Sabal minor, Vaccinium arboreum, and Vitis sp. In damp humus under pine needle litter.
locality: Geneva Wilderness Area, along Loop Trail, ca. 16 m S of deviation to amphitheater, ca. 0.40 mi. SSW of parking area off County Road 425.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. An investigation of the evolution and taxonomy of the true blueberries (Vaccinium section Cyanococcus).]; Clonal shrub 0.8 m tall, clone ca. 3 m diameter; aerial stems green to base; leaves lustrous deep green above, pale green beneath; pedicels and young fruit green. Common.
habitat: Deciduous forest with Gelsemium sempervirens, Ilex coriacea, Lyonia fruticosa, Lyonia lucida, Morella cerifera, Quercus nigra, Q. virginiana, Sabal minor, Vaccinium darrowii, V. fuscatum, V. elliottii, V. stamineum, and Vitis rotundifolia. In forest shade, damp sandy loam with dark brown organic matter, thin leaf litter, near a shallow culvert.
locality: Lake Okahumpka Park, ca. 9 m E of main entrance road along S side of trail, ca. 150 m from main entrance at E County Road 44.

recordedBy: Peter W. Fritsch; Paul S. Manos
occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. Common.
habitat: White sand mesic flatwoods, open, with Lyonia fruiticosa, Lyonia lucida, Quercus minima, Sabal etonia, and Vaccinium darrowii. In white sand, open sun sun.
locality: Archbold Biological Station, ca. 0.17 mi. N of the main parking area, ca. 30 m W of railroad tracks on W side of dirt road paralleling the tracks.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. Frequent.
habitat: Recently burned longleaf pine savanna with grasses, Pinus palustris, and Pteridium aquilinum; no Vaccinium darrowii observed in area. In dry white sand, very little leaf litter, open sun.
locality: Julington-Durbin Creek Preserve, along northern spur trail off N part of Yellow Blaze Loop Trail, ca. 1.5 mi. W of parking area.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. Common.
habitat: Longleaf pine savanna with Ilex coriacea, Lyonia fruticosa, Morella cerifera, Pinus palustris, Sabal minor, Salix sp.; Vaccinium corymbosum present on slope adjacent to pond. locality: Okefenokee National Wildlife Refuge, E edge of pond along W side of Wildlife Drive, ca. 0.55 mi. due S of Boat House Road.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. habitat: Longleaf and sand pine forest with Ilex coriacea, Lyonia lucida, Pinus clausa, P. palustris, Quercus myrtifolia, and Sabal minor. In slightly damp white sand under thick leaf litter, partial shade along trail.
locality: Geneva Wilderness Area, along W side of Flagler Trail, ca. 18 m SSW of parking area off County Road 425.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. Frequent.
habitat: Longleaf pine savanna with Pinus palustris, Serenoa repens, grasses. In damp white sand with organic material, open sun.
locality: Disney Wilderness Preserve, western stretch of the yellow trail, ca. 0.5 mi. due S of the junction with the red trail and ca. 1 mi. SSE of the main buildings.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. An investigation of the evolution and taxonomy of the true blueberries (Vaccinium section Cyanococcus).]; Clonal shrub 1.2 m tall; older stems gray, fissured, current-year stems green flushed dull pink; leaves slightly bluish green glaucous above (bloom rubs off, then surfaces green), whitish green beneath; fruit whitish green flushed dull pink, glaucous, limb pink. All plants of this form sampled in this area have stipitate glands on leaves beneath. Common.
habitat: Longleaf pine forest with Ilex coriacea, Pinus palustris, Quercus myrtifolia, Sabal minor, Vaccinium arboreum, and Vitis sp. In damp humus under pine needle litter.
locality: Geneva Wilderness Area, along Loop Trail, ca. 30 m S of deviation to amphitheater, ca. 0.41 mi. SSW of parking area off County Road 425.

occurrenceRemarks: Duplicates deposited at: BRIT, DUKE. [U.S. National Science Foundation DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217. Frequent.
habitat: Edge of mixed low forest above drainage ditch along road with Acer rubrum, Aristida stricta, Gaylussacia nana, Ilex coriacea, Lyonia fruticosa, L. lucida, Persea borbonia, Pinus elliottii, Sabal minor, Vaccinium arboreum, V. corymbosum, V. elliottii, V. fuscatum, and V. stamineum. In sandy clay under thin leaf litter, in full sun.
locality: Sam's Road, N side, ca. 100 m W of Laura Walker Road (Hwy. 177), ca. 0.9 mi. due S of US 82.

occurrenceRemarks: With Don Fraser; a visit to see what was around. We drove only Rattlesnake Camp Road and 3 Bridges Road. Nearly the only nectar sources were some Nuttall's Thistles and several Buttonbushes. All species with multiple records represent different individuals. Every patch of Buttonbushes had one or more Dukes' Skippers; pretty amazing. The weather at the start was sunny and 88 degrees ("feels like" 93), with a light breeze. We left around 1415.

occurrenceRemarks: With Don Fraser; an unsuccessful search for Dusky Roadside Skippers -- but we saw lots of other taxa. My camera, my sixth Panasonic Lumix FZ80, died within 2 hours of arriving here, so I was depressed and frustrated for the final 90 or so, having to take photographs with my Galaxy A52 cell phone. We stayed north of Forest Road 22 always and were mostly west of the Purple Trail that runs northwest-to-southeast through the sandhills. The weather at the end was partly sunny, 86 degrees ("feels like" 92), and breezy (from the south at 12 MPH, gusting to 18). The mostly overcast conditions and the winds depressed butterfly activity. We left here at 1334 and headed to Tillis Hill campground.

occurrenceRemarks: With Don Fraser; a visit to see what we could find. We spent time at three sites: two along Thunder Crossing Road north of Gopher Road, and one along Gopher Road east of Thunder Crossing Road. I am reporting the following animal taxa: 6 birds, 28 butterflies (including 7 skippers and 3 hairstreaks), 16 moths (including maybe a lifer), and 5 robber flies (including maybe a lifer). The weather at the start was sunny and 79 degrees ("feels like" 85) with calm winds. The weather at the end was sunny and 94 degrees ("feels like" 101) with calm winds. We left at 1316 at headed to Hardee's for lunch. My complete bird list: 1 Downy Woodpecker (*ph,) 1 Chimney Swift (*ph.) 4 Barn Swallows (*ph,) 1 Bank Swallow 1 Cliff Swallow (orange rump seen well) 1 Northern Parula (*ph,) 1 Prairie Warbler (*ph,) 1 Pine Warbler (*ph,) 1 Pine Warbler (*ph,) 2 Eastern Towhees (*ph,)

occurrenceRemarks: Avon Park butterfly count organized by Linda Cooper; with Don Fraser and Clint Gibson and two others (an Air Force botanist and Archbold Biological Station's Red-cockaded Woodpecker biologist) who drove in a separate truck and left after 1430. We mainly covered Frostproof and Willingham roads, but also drove Billig Grade and Bravo Road. We drove the roads slowly, stopping when we found nectar sources. Strangely, despite the abundance of Pickerelweed, there were very few blooms. There was only one patch of Redroot. Nonetheless, it was a good hairstreak and skipper day, with our group finding 3 hairstreak species -- including an exceptional one (a lifer)! -- and 18 skipper species. I was impressed with the number of Little Metalmarks; I photographed 4. I also got at least two lifer moths, a lifer wasp, a lifer dragonfly, a lifer grasshopper, a lifer robber fly, a lifer orchid, and undoubtedly several other lifer plant species. The weather at the start was sunny and 77 degrees ("feels like" 77) with a light breeze. By the end, it was sunny, 93 degrees ("feels like" 100), with a light breeze. We left at 1429, after 7 hours and 40 minutes onsite. Don treated me to a delicious pizza dinner at the Mellow Mushroom in Clearwater. Note: the dial that sets the exposure on my Panasonic Lumix FZ80 stopped working this past Monday, so Don Fraser loaned me an FZ200 -- the pre-cursor to the FZ80 -- that he bought used from a friend a year ago but has never used. The FZ200 has far less zoom (24x vs. 60x) and has different controls compared to the FZ80. Some controls took me a while to master today, but I eventually got the hang of it. In fact, I am very impressed with the quality of many of today's images. I will continue to use the FZ200 until my FZ80 -- still under warranty -- is replaced.

occurrenceRemarks: With Don Fraser, Clint Gibson, and John Lampkin; a mostly butterflying trip. We visited many spots, including Tillis Campground and Forest Road 8 west of Forest Road 13, but we spent more time along Forest Road 20 west of Forest Road 13 than at any other spot. The weather at the start was mostly cloudy and 52 degrees with calm winds. It warmed up considerably by the end. Clint and John left, and Don and I remained until we left at 1534, after more than 7 hours. Forest Road 13 was too rough for Jet to exit the Forest to the north, so I turned around and drove south all the way back to County Road 480.

occurrenceRemarks: A bioblitz organized by Alice Herden, who found a stray dog on the drive in, and stayed with the dog for a few hours, missing the bioblitz! This is Part I of the blitz, with Karen Salman; we walked the 1.5-mile nature trail clockwise then returned to the parking area, where Alice, her husband, and the dog awaited us. The weather at the start was sunny and 72 degrees ("feels like" 72), with calm winds. The others left at 1012, while I headed back out to explore the powerline cut and the northwestern part of the Area, which will be Part 2. Note: to compensate for my poor hearing, I used the Merlin program on my phone to identify and record bird vocalizations. I made 30 Merlin recordings, which I need to edit and upload, a process that likely will take a long time.

A solo visit because I was bored and needed to find something. Other than three pawpaw bushes and one lupine, the only plants blooming were blueberries. Several moths and a few butterflies escaped my photographs, but it was a good day for grasshoppers. I found three moths, one photographed (I thought the images were in focus when I was taking them), and another was very tine -- maybe 1/4 inch -- and in a weird shape. I hoping that iNat's AI can help with the ID. The weather at the start was sunny and 83 degrees, with a light breeze occasionally becoming breezy. I left at 1519.

occurrenceRemarks: This area was burned on January 7th, 2021 (a little over 6 weeks prior to this observation) as part of a prescribed fire program to keep pine rockland preserves healthy. We have had a couple rainy days in the past two weeks so I came by to appreciate the phoenix-esque magic of the pine rocklands habitat. Photo twelve days after the burn here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/68352405 I went a little crazy in the hour and a half I spent and photographed many plants in different stages of coming up. My favorite was Sporobolus junceus in full bloom: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/70021405 All observations from today here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?nelat=25.667871519762745&nelng=-80.34393682199925&on=2021-02-22&order_by=observed_on&place_id=any&swlat=25.665212208457042&swlng=-80.35414530950993&user_id=joemdo&verifiable=any
